snippet.textDisplay:
2:23

Bonus Urine Fact:
Yuri Gagarin was of course the first human in space : a Soviet union cosmonaut. During the bus ride out to his rocket - Vostok 1, he realised he had to pee. He decided to relieve himself on a back tire of the bus. For the cosmonauts who came after, it was considered bad luck not to do this on one's journey out to the launch pad also. The tradition endures today. (Given to anatomical constraints within a spacesuit, ladies generally prepare the urine beforehand in a small bottle or vial and deposit it with a throw.)

Apparently there was a somewhat similar tradition before US shuttle launches of playing poker until the commander lost a hand, thereby using up all of the day's bad luck.

Humans.


You're welcome

snippet.textDisplay: The bad news is we are not going to space any time soon (the physiological challenges and the cost in resources are just ridiculous). Even if we were, it would be just the expression of the same old drive to conquer and control that lead us to the mass extinction of easy prey, soil depletion, and also empires and slavery (one of these two is gone, replaced by the more efficient capitalism and its unprecedented wealth disparities); it's the same drive to that 'destination', the brass ring we fetishised while ignoring what we have. The good news is : we have fantastic challenges down here, how to regenerate our soils, how to deal with inequality and power, diseases, how to use science to produce rational technology. we have eons of work to make our Earth a paradise for ourselves. otherwise we'll just be majing our problems bigger. Europeans did not become wiser by sailing to Australia. When they did, they came 'in peace', or with whatever claim that made sense at that time. Our claims to  airless, lifeless, soilless planets, hostile places is none the wiser. Petty squabbles down on Earth will be exported to places that we are wholly inadapted to.

snippet.textDisplay:
For those of you who don't want to pause at 2:22 :

Bonus Urine Fact:
Yuri Gagarin was of course the first human in space; a Soviet Union cosmonaut. During the bus ride out to his rocket - Vostok 1, he realised he had to pee. He decided to relieve himself on a back tire of the bus. For the cosmonauts who came after, it was considered bad luck not to do this on one's journey out to the launch pad also. The tradition endures oday. (Given to anatomical constraints within a spacesuit, ladies generally prepare the urine beforehand in a small bottle or vial and deposit it with a throw.)

Apparently there was a somewhat similar tradition before US shuttle launches of play poker until the commander lost a hand, thereby using up all of the day's bad luck.

Humans.

snippet.textDisplay:
Brilliantly scripted.
They walked on the moon on my fifth birthday ( GMT) and I had all of those hopes and dreams. This was it, no more going back. My children would go into space. I waited, for a bright future. No more people trying to take over the world, we’d be meeting creatures from other planets, this would be our time.
All of these thoughts, in a little boy’s mind, unexplainable..but ...there.
Then suddenly we got bored, we stopped challenging ourselves. We never thought collectively. We went back to fighting, trying to take over the world again, with no thought of the future. I cried, when they pulled the Apollo missions, then, they tried to debunk the whole thing.
Hopefully others, with far greater minds and funds than I, shared similar feelings as me, and will go back and beyond beyond where, it was said that apparently, we had gone before. Hopefully, before our past technology and achievements, are forgotten by the next civilisation.
